Alcatel-Lucent, CGGVeritas, Poweo, Total: French Equity Preview

-- B y   F r a n c o i s   d e   B e a u p u y
-- 
2011-06-27T04:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-26/alcatel-lucent-cggveritas-poweo-total-french-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose stocks may have unusual price changes in Paris. Symbols
are in parentheses after company names and prices are from the
last close.  France’s  CAC 40 Index (CAC)  fell 2.99 points, or less than 0.1
percent, to 3,784.80 in Paris. The broader SBF 120 Index also
declined less than 0.1 percent to 2,852.02 points.  Alcatel-Lucent SA (ALU FP): Chief Executive Officer Ben Verwaayen is “very confident” the telecommunications equipment
maker will meet its 2011 targets, Investir reported, citing an
interview. The group’s results should continue improving after
2011, Verwaayen said, according to the newspaper. Shares in the
company gained 0.5 percent to 3.68 euros.  CGGVeritas (GA FP): The seismic surveyor of oilfields sees
business returning to a “high” level in the second half
following a “seasonally” quiet second quarter, Investir
reported, citing Chief Executive Officer Jean-Georges Malcor.
Shares in CGGVeritas fell 0.8 percent to 23.27 euros.  Poweo (ALPWO)  SA: Verbund AG is in talks about selling
its 46 percent stake in French utility Poweo SA to Enel SpA or
Eni SpA, Le Journal du Dimanche reported, without saying where
it got the information. The talks are at a preliminary stage and
a decision may be made in several months, the newspaper said.
Poweo shares rose 1 percent to 4.04 euros.  Publicis Groupe SA (PUB)  : The French advertising company
may spend about 700 million euros ($992 million) on acquisitions
this year, compared with a previous target of 400 million to 500
million euros, Chief Executive Officer  Maurice Levy  said in an
interview on June 24. The increased spending won’t have an
impact on the company’s forecasts, Levy said. Shares in Publicis
fell 0.5 percent to 37.71 euros.  Total SA (FP)  : France’s Industry Minister Eric Besson
said on June 24 that Total SA, some other  oil companies , and
several supermarket chains agreed to modify gasoline prices
after the  International Energy Agency  said its members agreed to
release crude from strategic reserves, prompting a reduction in
the cost of the raw material. Shares in Total gained 0.1 percent
to 37.995 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Francois De Beaupuy in Paris at 
